body:
When reading [the Chapter04-02 references and borrowing of The Rust Programming Language Book](https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing.html), I know that it cannot be allowed to exits mutable reference and immutable reference simultaneously. 

Here is the official demo:

```rust
let mut s = String::from("hello");

let r1 = &s; // no problem
let r2 = &s; // no problem
let r3 = &mut s; // BIG PROBLEM

println!("{}, {}, and {}", r1, r2, r3);
```
Here is error:
```
error[E0502]: cannot borrow `s` as mutable because it is also borrowed as immutable
 --> src/main.rs:6:14
  |
4 |     let r1 = &s; // no problem
  |              -- immutable borrow occurs here
5 |     let r2 = &s; // no problem
6 |     let r3 = &mut s; // BIG PROBLEM
  |              ^^^^^^ mutable borrow occurs here
7 |
8 |     println!("{}, {}, and {}", r1, r2, r3);
  |                                -- immutable borrow later used here
```

But when changing variable to function parameter, ***it is allowed!!!!***

```rust
fn main() {
    let mut s = String::from("demo");

    let len1 = cal_len_immut(&s);
    let len2 = cal_len_mut(&mut s);

}
fn cal_len_immut(s: &String) -> usize {
    s.len()
}

fn cal_len_mut(s: &mut String) -> usize {
    s.push_str(", world!");
    s.len()
}
```
As a result, when in multithreads, it will lead to race condition if the immutable reference passing to cal_len_immut in a read thread, while the mutable reference passing to cal_len_mut in a write thread.
